{"cells":[{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"# Lab: Connect Types and Traverse the Data Model","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Overview","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After you create Types, you will need to connect them in your data model. This is similar to setting up foreign keys in a traditional relational database management system. \n\n<div class=\"alert alert-success\">\n    Each learning objective corresponds with a <b>#TODO</b> in the notebook activities.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Estimated time","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"This lab will take approximately **1 hour** to complete.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### Learning objectives","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After completing this lab, you will be able to:\n- Connect Types in a data model using collection and reference fields.\n- Recognize collection field syntax.\n- Implement collection field arrays with foreign key filters.\n- Traverse a data model with dot notation.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Lab support","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"For guidance on the activities, please refer to the <a href=\"../src/doc/connect-and-traverse-data-model-solution.c3doc.md\">solutions</a>. You can also refer to the [troubleshooting tips and tricks](../labs/troubleshooting.md) if you run into issues.\n\nFor additional support, check out the <a href=\"https://learn.c3.ai/page/help-center\" target=\"_blank\">Help Center</a> for office hours information.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Setup","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 1. Prerequisites","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Lab 1, `create-and-query-persistable-types.c3nb`, is a prerequisite for completing the activities in this lab. ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 2. Application selection","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"When you complete this C3 notebook, you want to run the commands against the right application. Before you continue with the lab, open the dropdown menu by selecting **Select Application** in the toolbar. This displays a list of applications in your environment. Choose the application with `root package: academyFundamentals`. \n\n\nIn the following image, the application with the root package `academyfundamentals` is selected:\n\n<img src=\"../src/doc/img/lab2/app-dropdown.png\" alt=\"The dropdown menu with the academyfundamentals application selected.\" width=\"700px\" style=\"padding: inherit; margin:auto; display:block;\"/> ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 3. Move data files in your package","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"There are folders in `resources/` containing data for the `City`, `LineItem`, `Product`, `Sale`, and `Store` Types. \n\nMove these folders to the `data` folder. The data folder should have the following structure:\n\n```js\nacademyFundamentals/\n├── data/\n│   ├── City/\n│   │   └── City.csv\n│   ├── LineItem/\n│   │   └── LineItem.csv\n│   ├── Product/\n│   │   └── Product.csv\n│   ├── Sale/\n│   │   └── Sales.csv\n│   └── Store/\n│   │   └── Store.csv\n├── labs/\n└── ...\n```\n\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n    Ensure your <code>data/</code> folder has the same structure, where each CSV is in the folder corresponding to the Type name.\n    <br><br>\n    Not following this structure will result in failing to upload the data to your application.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 4. Upload sample data","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Run the following cell to upload data necessary for this project. **Ensure you have completed the previous steps before uploading the data.**","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"// Remove any existing records in the City, Store, and Product Types.\nUtil.checkExistingRecords()\n\n","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["Successfully removed existing City, Store, and Product records."]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779395528176,"endTime":1779395528432},"executionOrder":1,"success":true}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"// This command uploads the Type data to your application and will output any errors that occur with the Type data upload.\nPkg.upsertAllSeed()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["[]"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779395536071,"endTime":1779395541457},"executionOrder":2,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"### 5. Verify data load","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Run the following command to verify that data has uploaded successfully.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Util.checkPostUpsert()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["All Types have the expected number of records."]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779395546516,"endTime":1779395546595},"executionOrder":3,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Introduction","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"After building out the Types required for your application data model, your next task is to connect the Types together and model their relationships. You use reference fields and collection fields to connect the Types in your data model together. \n\nThe following ERD shows you the fields you modify in your data model and connections you set up in this lab:\n\n<img src=\"../src/doc/img/lab2/ERD-highlighted.png\" alt=\"ERD highlighted with the portions a user completes in the lab.\" width=\"700px\" style=\"padding: inherit;\n  margin:auto; display:block;\"/> ","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"## Section 1: Create reference fields","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"In your Type definitions, primitive fields might not capture the relationships between certain Types. Consider the SmartBulb use case. How do you model a particular SmartBulb located in a specific Fixture using only primitive fields? Reference fields enable you to model these relationships and references in your application data model.\n\nExamine the following code block, which contains the SmartBulb definition with the `fixture` reference field:\n\n```javascript\nentity type SmartBulb {\n\n    /**\n     * The fixture the smart bulb is currently in.\n     */\n    fixture: Fixture\n    \n}\n```\n\nThis field definition indicates that a SmartBulb record may point to a Fixture record. Notice that the field data type, `Fixture`, is another Type. A reference field points to an instance of another Type. You can think of reference fields as defining a foreign key reference in traditional database systems.\n\n<div class=\"alert alert-warning\">\n    Recall the naming conventions for Types and fields. Fields use camelCase and Types use PascalCase. In the example earlier, <code>fixture</code> is the field name since it follows camelCase, and <code>Fixture</code> is a Type, since it follows PascalCase.\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"<div class=\"alert alert-info\">\n<h4>Activity 1.1</h4>\nUpdate the following Types in your data model to change the primitive fields to reference fields:\n\n<ul>\n    <li><code>Store.c3typ</code>: update the <code>city</code> field to a reference field.</li>\n    <li><code>LineItem.c3typ</code>: update the <code>product</code> reference field and the <code>sale</code> reference field.</li>\n    <li><code>Sale.c3typ</code>: implement the <code>store</code> reference field.</li>\n</ul>\n</div>","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"If you're stuck, refer to [Lab Support](#lab-support) or additional guidance.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"##### Test your implementation","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"You may have to refresh the data in your Type after adding reference fields. Run the following command to upload the data in the `data/` folder into their respective Types.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Pkg.upsertAllSeed()","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"text/plain","value":["[]"]}]}],"executionSummary":{"timing":{"startTime":1779396489249,"endTime":1779396491797},"executionOrder":6,"success":true}},{"kind":1,"languageId":"markdown","value":"Run the following cell to test your reference fields by using dot notation. Dot notation is covered in detail in [Section 3](#section-3-data-model-traversal) of this lab.","output":[],"executionSummary":{}},{"kind":2,"languageId":"javascript","value":"Store.fetch({filter: Filter.eq('city.name', 'San Francisco')})","output":[{"items":[{"mime":"c3/notebook","value":["{","\t\"kind\": \"JSON\",","\t\"output\": {","\t\t\"data\": {","\t\t\t\"objs\": [","\t\t\t\t{","\t\t\t\t\t\"id\": \"store_001\",","\t\t\t\t\t\"meta\": {","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"appCode\": 1865745090558541600,","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"env\": \"srinat\",","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"app\": \"academyfundamentals\",","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"created\": \"2026-05-21T20:32:18Z\",","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"createdBy\": \"provisioner\",","\t\t\t\t\t\t\"updated\": \"2026-05-21